:INFO
The Technology History That Starts With a Poet
The Innovators opens with Ada Lovelace, the daughter of Lord Byron who wrote what \
is considered the first algorithm more than a century before computers existed. \
Walter Isaacson uses her as a frame for the book's central argument: that the \
great technological achievements of the digital age were collaborative, not solo, \
and that the myth of the lone genius inventor misrepresents what actually happened. \
The Ada chapter alone is worth the price of the book.

